comments.body: Member of the Alumni Records Office who directly request these reports have been updated as to the status of the 2022 thesis submissions (as these are still under review in DataSpace).

I am still experiencing difficulties troubleshooting the deployment of `rt4ds` with the following error:

```bash
INFO: validateJarFile(/mnt/disks/oarstagingdatastore/prod-copy/dspace/webapps.static/rt4ds/WEB-INF/lib/servlet-api-2.5.jar) - jar not loaded. See Servlet Spec 3.0, section 10.7.2. Offending class: javax/servlet/Servlet.class
```

Referencing the [specification](https://download.oracle.com/otn-pub/jcp/servlet-3.0-fr-eval-oth-JSpec/servlet-3_0-final-spec.pdf?AuthParam=1659102911_4fddb0c8af6dcae9ef59bea5c4abcdbf), I find the following:

> # 10.7.2 Web Application Class Loader
> The class loader that a container uses to load a servlet in a WAR must allow the developer to load any resources contained in library JARs within the WAR following normal Java SE semantics using getResource. As described in the Java EE license agreement, servlet containers that are not part of a Java EE product should not allow the application to override Java SE platform classes, such as those in the java.* and javax.* namespaces, that Java SE does not allow to be modified. The container should not allow applications to override or access the container’s implementation classes. It is recommended also that the application class loader be implemented so that classes and resources packaged within the WAR are loaded in preference to
classes and resources residing in container-wide library JARs. An implementation MUST also guarantee that for every web application deployed in a container, a call to Thread.currentThread.getContextClassLoader() MUST return a ClassLoader instance that implements the contract specified in this section. Furthermore, the ClassLoader instance MUST be a separate instance for each deployed web application. The container is required to set the thread context ClassLoader as described above before making any callbacks (including listener
callbacks) into the web application, and set it back to the original ClassLoader, once the callback returns.
```

Removing a redundant JAR dependency within the `staging` environment (`servlet-api-2.5.jar`) seems to have assisted in resolving this, however, the  `rt4ds` endpoint still seems to fail to deploy:

```bash

orangelight.title: i2889 don't allow users to add more than 1000 bookmarks

comments.body:
@sandbergja these are my observations from deploying in catalog-qa and playing around with bookmarks:

1. When I'm logged in and have 1000 bookmarks if I select one at a time I get an alert.  When I close the alert the bookmark stays with a button caption 'Saving...'. Going to a different page removes the 'Saving...'

2. If a user clicks on 'Bookmark all', they'll get the same alert like before and they would need to close it for all the bookmarks that are on the results page. The bookmark button has the 'Saving...' caption, because it can't complete the action to bookmark the record. Going to a different page removes the 'Saving...'

3. If I have already more than 1000 saved bookmarks and I click 'Bookmarks', when I try to visit the bookmarks page I still get the 'Sorry I don't understand your search'. If I try to save a bookmark I get the **1**. If I try to save many bookmarks at once I get the **2**.  In both cases the record cannot be bookmarked and 'Saving...' remains as a caption. Going to a different page removes the 'Saving...
4. The alert looks different than the one you have in the screenshot. I've attached a screenshot.
5. In production there are currently 4 user_ids with more than 1000 saved bookmarks. Bookmarks who belong to a specific user_id that does not exist in Users table should be removed. (This is a different ticket. https://github.com/pulibrary/orangelight/issues/3090 I believe we have many users that are not in the users table anymore but their bookmarks exist)
The active users that have more than 1000 bookmarks are 3. We should discuss in our meeting to reach out to the users and help them to reduce their bookmarks. I believe as it is right now they can't access the bookmarks page at all.
In order to get the users that have more than 1000 bookmarks I run in catalog1 in the rails console : `Bookmark.group(:user_id).count.select{|k,v| v > 999}`

![Screen Shot 2022-07-29 at 2 45 20 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9905193/181824729-3ac325a0-71e4-4bee-b345-252860722499.png)

comments.body:
@maxkadel 

1. We definitely use local identifier. You can see it imported here: https://figgy.princeton.edu/catalog/c2e1f051-73c6-43ba-a8cb-651a89fdd8f1, and these identifiers are used for synchronizing with Getty for https://cicognara.org

2. `identifier` should be ARKs that are in the 856, I believe? I'm not sure where that'd be in the solr record, exactly. The idea is that if there's already an ARK in there, it should import it. I think it'll only be a IIIF ARK if it was put in there from someone importing it from Figgy. I'm working from memory, but I think there used to be some logic in there to try to pick the right 856 if there were multiple, but I could be wrong.

3. I suspect this is just a side effect of the Alma -> Solr direct pipeline in Bibdata being pretty rough, since it didn't have all the data that the bulk export has. I think it's fine as you have it.
@tpendragon - am I understanding correctly that right now local_identifier should only include the Cicognara number?
